    colourp1: "The color in a scientific poster is more than just a decoration. This is a powerful tool that helps you highlight important things, organize visual structure, and make information more accessible. The ability to work with color and contrast correctly is a step towards a professional, readable and aesthetically pleasing design.",
    colourp2: "Color as an accent. Color is able to direct the viewer's gaze and emphasize key elements. Use it to highlight headlines, graphs, or meaningful data, such as totals or conclusions. Choose a basic palette of 2-3 colors to avoid visual overload. You can combine similar colors, those that are next to each other on the color wheel, blue and blue, pink and purple. Another way is to choose complementary colors, those that are located opposite each other: orange and blue. Remember that color is a tool. A poster that is too colorful may seem unprofessional and frivolous. Think about what effect you need.",
    colourp3: "Readability is the main criterion for a successful poster. The contrast between the text and the background should be sufficient so that the information is visible from a distance and under different lighting conditions. It is better to leave the background of the poster white. If the text of the chart legend is located on a colored bar, check the contrast. You can use the Colorable online service. It checks the ratio of the two entered colors. An acceptable result is marked with three letters A.",
    colourp4: "The harmonious color scheme makes the poster complete and professional. Using the same colors for related elements, such as headings and subheadings, helps structure the material. rainbow schemes and multi-colored blocks. Choose one color for each type of information (for example, blue for headlines, green for graphs). If the graphs that you have modeled in a third-party program already have a specific color palette, you can adjust to it.",
